# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The ***Almanach de Gotha*** (German: *Gothaischer Hofkalender*, pronounced [ˈɡoːtaɪʃɐ ˈhoːfkaˌlɛndɐ]) is a directory of Europe's royalty and higher nobility, also including the major governmental, military and diplomatic corps, as well as statistical data by country.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] It was published annually from 1785 until 1944 by Justus Perthes Publishing House in Gotha.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1992, the family of Justus Perthes re-established its right to use the name *Almanach de Gotha*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1998, a London-based publisher, John Kennedy, acquired the rights for use of the title of *Almanach de Gotha* from Justus Perthes Verlag Gotha GmbH, then a fully owned subsidiary of Ernst Klett Schulbuchverlag GmbH, Stuttgart.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The last edition produced by Justus Perthes was the 181st, produced in 1944.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] After a gap of 54 years the first of the new editions (the 182nd) was published in 1998 with English, the new diplomatic language, used as the *lingua franca* in the place of French or German.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Perthes regards the resultant volumes as new works, and not as a continuation of the editions which Perthes had published from 1785 to 1944.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Two volumes have been printed since 1998, with Volume I containing lists of the sovereign, formerly sovereign and mediatised houses of Europe, and a diplomatic and statistical directory; and Volume II containing lists of the non-sovereign princely and ducal houses of Europe.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The original *Almanach de Gotha* provided detailed facts and statistics on nations of the world, including their reigning and formerly reigning houses, those of Europe being more complete than those of other continents.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] It also named the highest incumbent officers of state, members of the diplomatic corps, and Europe's upper nobility with their families.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] At its most extensive the *Almanach* had more than 1200 pages, fewer than half of which were dedicated to monarchical or aristocratic data.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] It acquired a reputation for the breadth and precision of its information on royalty and nobility compared to other almanacs.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The *Almanach'*s publication by Justus Perthes began at the ducal court of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha in Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The almanac listed the reigning dynasty of that court first well into the 19th century, usually followed by kindred sovereigns of the House of Wettin and then, in alphabetical order, other families of princely rank, reigning and non-reigning.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Although always published in French, other almanacs in French and English were more widely sold internationally.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The almanac's structure changed and its scope expanded over the years.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The second portion, called the *Annuaire diplomatique et statistique* ("Diplomatic and Statistical Yearbook"), provided demographic and governmental information by nation, similar to other almanacs.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Its first portion, called the *Annuaire généalogique* ("Genealogical Yearbook"), came to consist essentially of three sections: reigning and formerly reigning families, mediatized families and non-sovereign families at least one of whose members bore the title of prince or duke.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The first section always listed Europe's sovereign houses, whether they reigned as emperor, king, grand duke, duke, prince, or some other title such as prince elector, margrave, landgrave, count palatine or pope.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1812, these entries began to be listed in groups: first were German sovereigns who held the rank of grand duke or prince elector and above (the Duke of Saxe-Gotha was, however, listed here along with, but before, France—see below).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Listed next were Germany's reigning ducal and princely dynasties under the heading "College of Princes", e.g.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Hohenzollern, Isenburg, Leyen, Liechtenstein and the other Saxon duchies.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] They were followed by heads of non-German monarchies, such as Austria, Brazil, and Great Britain.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Fourth were listed non-reigning dukes and princes, whether mediatized or not, including La Rochefoucauld (including Dominique and his son Gabriel), Arenberg, Croy, Fürstenberg alongside Batthyany, Jablonowski, Sulkowski, Porcia and Benevento.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1841 a third section was added to those of the sovereign dynasties and the non-reigning princely and ducal families.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The 1815 treaty of the Congress of Vienna had authorized – and Article 14 of the German Confederation's *Bundesakt* (charter) recognized – retention from the German Imperial regime of equality of birth for marital purposes of mediatized families (called *Standesherren*) to reigning dynasties.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1877, the mediatized comital families were moved from section III to section II A, where they joined the princely mediatized families.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In the third section were members of such non-reigning but historically notable princely or ducal families such as Rohan, Orsini, Ursel, Norfolk, Czartoryski, Galitzine, La Rochefoucauld, Kinsky, Radziwill, Merode, Dohna and Alba.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Arenberg, Biron, Dadiani, Boncompagni-Ludovisi, Giray, Murat) did not benefit from a similar interpretation of their historical status in the almanac.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Even in the early 19th century there were objections to the almanac's retention of deposed dynasties, although not necessarily the desired changes.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The response of the publishers was to humour Napoleon by producing two editions: one for France, with the recently ennobled, and another which included dynasties deposed since abolition of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] A merged version, whose first section (Princely houses) included recently reigning dynasties but also the titulature of families that lost sovereignty after the fall of Napoleon in 1815, remained in publication as *Gothaischer Hofkalender* (Gothaic court calendar).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The almanac was published in a German and a French edition as *Gothaischer Hofkalender* and *Almanach de Gotha*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1887 the *Almanach* began to include non-European dynasties in its first section, with the inclusion of one of the ruling families of India.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The *court calendar* was later expanded to include the four series of volumes for the German and Austrian *comital houses* (*i.e.*, counts' families, since 1825), the *baronial houses* (since 1848), the untitled *Uradel houses* (since 1900) and the untitled *Briefadel houses* (since 1907).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The series continued until 1944, but in 1939 its title *Gotha court calendar* was changed to *Gothaisches genealogisches Taschenbuch* ("Gothan Genealogical Pocket Book").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] This format has since been widely replicated in dynastic compilations (*e.g.*, *Genealogisches Handbuch des Adels*, *Fürstliche Häuser*, Burke's Royal Families of the World, *Le Petit Gotha*, Ruvigny's "Titled Nobility of Europe").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] After Soviet troops entered Gotha in 1945, the city became part of Communist East Germany and the publisher ceased operations.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] From 1951 to 2013, a different publisher, *C.A.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Starke* of Limburg, West Germany, published a multi-volume German-language publication entitled the **Genealogisches Handbuch des Adels** (GHdA) - (Genealogical Handbook of Nobility).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The book series produced several volumes of all sections each year, often containing new, first-time post-war entries, with the respective families being updated about once every 10 to 20 years.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 2013 the publisher *Starke Verlag* ceased to continue to publish new books in this series after a contract termination by the author.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Instead the **Gothaisches Genealogisches Handbuch** (GGH) − (Gothaic Genealogical Handbook) continues the annual publication of the substantially same content as GHdA since 2015.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The publisher and editor of the new GGH publication is the *Verlag des Deutschen Adelsarchivs* (publishing company of the *German Nobility Archive*).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] This archive of the *Union of German nobility associations* has always been the author of both GHdA and GGH.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In contentious questions, the *German Nobility Rights Committee* of this union decides.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] However, no single volume of the *Fürstliche Häuser* of GHdA or GGH includes *all* the families of German and European royal, princely and ducal families that were annually included in the *Hofkalender* or *Almanach de Gotha*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Rather, they are recorded alternately in successive volumes.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Therefore it is necessary to use multiple volumes to trace all of Europe's royal families.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] With regard to the current information, the archive works together with the respective family heads and is dependent on the cooperation and consent of the families for reasons of information privacy.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Because of this required legwork, not that many princely and ducal houses of France, the UK, Italy and other countries are included, while the German ones, as well as the ruling and formerly ruling royal families of Europe are covered quite reliably.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1992 the family of Justus Perthes re-established its right to the use of the name *Almanach de Gotha*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The company *Justus Perthes Verlag Gotha GmbH* (a subsidiary of *Ernst Klett Schulbuchverlag GmbH*) then sold these rights in 1995 to a new company, Almanach de Gotha Limited, formed in London.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The new publisher launched the 182nd edition on 16 March 1998 at Claridge's Hotel.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] It was written in English instead of French, as the editor felt that English was now the language of diplomacy.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Charlotte Pike served as editor of the 1998 edition only and John Kennedy as managing director and publisher.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The new publishers also revived the Committee of Patrons under the presidency of King Juan Carlos I of Spain and chairmanship of King Michael I of Romania.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Upon his death, King Michael was succeeded by Albert II, Prince of Monaco.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] A review in *The Economist* criticised the low editorial standards and attacked volume II for a lack of genealogical accuracy.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] A new edition of volume I was published in 2012 under the editorship of John James.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] A review in *The Times Literary Supplement* praised the 2012 volume I for a "punctilious itemisation of titles, lineage and heraldry [aiming] for scholarship rather than sensation ..." Since 2022, Italian publisher Ettore Gallelli has published the Gotha Calendar in Italian.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Europe's middle and lower nobility (families whose principal title ranked below that of prince or duke — except mediatized families, listed in a section of their own) were not included in the almanac.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Nor were the grandees or ducal families of Portugal and Spain (where titles, being transmissible through both male and female lines, were regularly inherited by descendants of non-patrilineal lineage).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Families of some Italian and East European nations (e.g.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Russia, Romania), where the princely title was claimed by many, were also incomplete.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Yet the reigning, formerly reigning and noble families included in the almanac numbered in the hundreds by the time the almanac ceased publication in 1944.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] In 1890 the almanac renamed II A to section II, and II B to section III.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Dynasties reigning over non-European nations were listed in section I B.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Families which became extinct were listed for the final time in the year following the death of the last member, male or female, and subsequent editions referred readers to that volume.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] From 1927, the almanac ceased to include all families in each year's edition, and instead rotated entries every few years.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Where titles and styles (such as Serene Highness) had ceased to be recognized by national governments (e.g.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] Titles of pretence below sovereign rank were accorded to members of formerly reigning dynasties as reported by heads of their houses, otherwise self-assumed titles were not used.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/almanach-de-gotha] The almanac included an explicit disclaimer announcing that known biographical details, such as birth dates and divorces, would not be suppressed.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Alois was born on 20 September 1933 at Zeil Castle near Leutkirch im Allgäu.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He was a son of Erich, 6th Prince of Waldburg-Zeil (1899–1953) and Princess Monika of Löwenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg (1905–1992).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] His elder brother was Georg, 7th Prince of Waldburg-Zeil.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He studied politics and economics at the University of Bonn, the Sapienza University of Rome, and the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil was from 1980 to 1998 member of German Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] On 21 June 1956, he married Clarissa, Countess von Schönborn-Wiesentheid (b.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Alois, Count von Waldburg-Zeil died on 14 December 2014.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Elisabeth was born in Reichenau on 7 July 1878, the youngest of a large family, as her father Archduke Karl Ludwig of Austria.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Elisabeth and her older sister Archduchess Maria Annunciata of Austria (later Abbess of the Theresia Convent in the Hradschin, Prague) was the result of her father's third marriage to her mother Infanta Maria Theresa of Portugal, daughter of the deposed King Miguel I of Portugal.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] In addition, her father was a younger brother of Franz Joseph I of Austria, the reigning emperor at the time of her birth.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] He was also a sibling of Maximilian I of Mexico, who became Emperor of Mexico for a short time.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Archduchess Elisabeth Amalie married Prince Alois of Liechtenstein in Vienna on 20 April 1903.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] There had been some debate as to whether this was an equal union.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] The bride's uncle Emperor Franz Joseph I attended the wedding with the intention of making it clear he regarded the House of Liechtenstein as a legitimate reigning dynasty.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] As the House of Liechtenstein had become sovereign, the couple were ruled equal in birth, and the Emperor was happy to see a member of his family making a dynastic marriage, after the morganatic marriage of her half-brother Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Later, the Emperor also became the godfather of the couple's eldest son, Franz Joseph, who was named after him.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Sometime after their marriage, Princess Catherine Radziwill commented that Elisabeth "is very pretty and resembles her mother more than the Habsburgs, whose lower lip she has not inherited by some kind of miracle, for which, I suppose, she feels immeasurably grateful".
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Elisabeth and Alois lived in various castles within Austria, including Gross-Ullersdorf Castle.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Their eldest son was born in Frauenthal Castle.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] She owned 31 motor cars and was regarded as one of the more enthusiastic motorists among imperial women in Europe.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] She converted the stables at her Hungarian castle Stuhlweissenburg to garages but pursued her hobby quietly and studiously, so that the great majority of the public were not even aware of her large collection.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Prince Alois renounced his rights to the succession on 26 February 1923, in favor of their son Franz Joseph, who would accede to the throne on 25 July 1938 as Franz Joseph II.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Prince Alois himself died on 17 March 1955 from influenza at Vaduz Castle in Liechtenstein.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-elisabeth-amalie-of-austria] Due to his renunciation, he never became the prince of Liechtenstein.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-helena-of-austria] Helena was born in Linz, Austria-Hungary, the second-eldest child and eldest daughter of Archduke Peter Ferdinand, Prince of Tuscany and his wife Princess Maria Cristina of Bourbon-Two Sicilies.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-helena-of-austria] Helena was raised with her three siblings in Salzburg and Vienna until the end of World War I in 1918 when her family was exiled and moved to Lucerne, Switzerland.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-helena-of-austria] Helena married Philipp Albrecht, Hereditary Duke of Württemberg, eldest child and son of Albrecht, Duke of Württemberg and his wife, Archduchess Margarete Sophie of Austria, on 24 October 1923 in Altshausen.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-helena-of-austria] Helena died just a week after giving birth to her daughter Maria Christina, aged only 20.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/archduchess-helena-of-austria] Her husband later married her sister Archduchess Rosa of Austria, Princess of Tuscany in 1928.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Clemens Graf von Waldburg-Zeil was born in Munich as the second of five children, and the eldest son of Alois Graf von Waldburg-Zeil und Trauchburg and his wife Clarissa (née Countess of Schönborn-Wiesentheid).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Since 1985, he is married to Princess Georgina von Liechtenstein, daughter of Dr.agr.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Georg Prinz von und zu Liechtenstein (son of Prince Aloys of Liechtenstein and Archduchess Elisabeth Amalie of Austria) and Marie-Christine, Duchess of Württemberg (daughter of Philipp Albrecht, Duke of Württemberg, and his first wife Archduchess Helena of Austria).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil is a first lieutenant in the German army reserve corps.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He received his basic training as a paratrooper and completed his service in the 10th maintenance battalion in Sigmaringen.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Clemens Graf von Waldburg-Zeil is a graduate in business administration.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He studied computer science and economics in Karlsruhe and Tübingen.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] From 1990 to 1995 he worked as a consultant and auditor for Dr.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Lipfert GmbH (later merged with PricewaterhouseCoopers) in Stuttgart.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Lipfert GmbH he also worked as a tax advisor and consultant for the company based in Berlin.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Thereafter between 1995 and 2002 he managed the finance department of the catholic Archdiocese of Berlin where he was also responsible for managing established subsidiaries including publishing and real estate companies.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] In 2003 Waldburg-Zeil accepted the position as secretary general (CEO, member of the board) of the German Red Cross based in Berlin.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He initiated a reorganization of the GRC to define a strategic framework for the governance of the German Red Cross, a federal system with 400.000 volunteers, 140.000 employees and a gross budget of 6 bn euros per year.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] The process culminated in the adoption of new regulatory statutes in 2009.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] That same year, Waldburg-Zeil was appointed chairman of the board (CEO) of the German Red Cross.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil is also very active in the international aid community through the GRCs work in providing foreign aid internationally (present in fifty countries for disaster management and development assistance) () with a current budget of 50 Mio p.a.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] At the beginning of 2003, Clemens Graf von Waldburg-Zeil took over the post of secretary-general of the German Red Cross (GRC).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He assumed strategic responsibility over more than 5000 legally independent divisions of the GRC, which comprised over 400.000 volunteers, 150.000 employees and seven billion euros in annual turnover.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Prior to his tenure, the GRC faced financial and organisational challenges, owed largely to its federalist structure.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil was able to implement a set of process improvements and innovations.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] As a result, the capital reserves of the GRC Federal Associan could build up to 53 million euros, following years of losses prior to Waldburg-Zeil's tenure.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] His overall legacy to the GRC was one of transformation – towards a more uniform and integrated association capable of initiating far-reaching improvement processes.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil's efforts culminated in a strategic initiative which he coined 2010plus.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] It was designed to solve further financial and operational challenges through newly created processes, while overcoming federal barriers.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] The 2010plus initiative was presented as a best practice template for large-scale change management projects in external non-profit organizations – such as the Protestant Church of Germany, and the Bertelmann foundation.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Under the leadership of Waldburg-Zeil, the GRC achieved an agreement on structured funding with the Ministry of Development, which reduced the GRC's dependency on obtaining funds in large scale emergency cases and helped establish long-term relationships with regions at risk.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] After a reorganization of the GRC, Waldburg-Zeil was appointed chairman of the board in 2009.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] In addition to achieving financial security, another major objective was to reestablish user rights to the names and symbols of the Red Cross.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Under the initiative of the GRC, the Red Cross Act, which dates back to the Second World War, was completely modernized by the Ministry of Justice and approved by the Bundestag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] All trademark rights to names and signs have been filed with the Trademark Court and all unlawful use of names and signs under trademark law have been prosecuted.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] On top of this, he was instrumental in integrating the ambulance and disaster relief services, providing them with easier access to funding.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] In the course of modernizing the German civil service and disaster protection act, Waldburg-Zeil became involved with the Bundestag's forum for future public safety, which eventually became a standalone association.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/clemens-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil is a founding member of the “Forum on the Future of Public Safety and Security” which was started in 2007 by members of the then German parliament, business companies and civil society.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Georg was born on 5 June 1928 in Würzburg.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] He was the son of Erich, 6th Prince of Waldburg-Zeil-Trauchburg (1899–1953) and Princess Monika of Löwenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg (1905–1992).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] He had six younger siblings, including Alois, Count of Waldburg-Zeil, a CDU member of the Bundestag (and father of Clemens, Count of Waldburg-Zeil), Princess Josefine von Lobkowicz, and his brother, Eberhard, Count of Waldburg zu Zeil and Trauchburg.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Blasien boarding school until it was closed by the National Socialists in 1939.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] After the end of the war, he obtained his *Abitur* (university entrance qualification) and studied at the Eberhard Karls University of Tübingen, where he graduated with a degree in economics in 1951.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Upon the death of his father in a car accident on 24 May 1953, he took over all of his father's businesses, two-thirds of which were agriculture and forestry in the Allgäu region, and one-third industrial in southern Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] He also succeeded his father as head of the former Princely House of Waldburg.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] In the 1950s he was one of the most important donors to the controversial right-wing conservative circle of the *Western Action*, deputy chairman of the Western Academy and publisher of its journal *Neues Abendland*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Also in the 1950s, Georg von Waldburg-Zeil, like his brother Alois, was a member of the conservative European Documentation and Information Centre (CEDI).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] In the course of the post-war land reform of the West German state of Württemberg-Hohenzollern initiated by the French post-World War II occupation zone in 1949, the House of Waldburg was one of the three longest-resistant opponents.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil and his family owned approximately 10,000 hectares of land, primarily used for forestry and agriculture, which made them one of the largest private landowners in Germany.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] He was also a publisher of the *Schwäbische Zeitung* through the media house Schwäbischer Verlag GmbH & Co.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] KG and was involved in the private broadcasters Radio 7, Radio Seefunk, three regional television stations and numerous other subsidiaries.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Since the 1960s he was co-editor of the *Allgäuer Zeitung* and the *Memminger Zeitung*.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Since the late 1970s, he owned the *Estancia* "San Jorge", the Argentine luxury winter sports resort of San Martín de los Andes, along with several thousand hectares of coniferous plantations, including 2,000 hectares reserved for red deer hunting.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] The Estancia's neighboring estates belong to the German industrialists Ruprecht von Haniel and Wolf von Buchholtz (together they own over 15,000 hectares of land).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] The family also formerly owned (together with the Feldmühle Group) the Baienfurt paper mill near Ravensburg, which was sold to Stora Enso in 1990 before closing at the end of 2008.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil was a member of the advisory boards of the Landesbank Baden-Württemberg, Germany's biggest state-backed landesbank lender, Deutsche Bank and served as President of the German Aero Club.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] On 23 October 1957 in Munich, Georg von Waldburg-Zeil married to Princess Marie Gabrielle of Bavaria (b.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] 1931), eldest daughter of Albert of Bavaria, the son of Rupprecht, the last Bavarian Crown Prince, by his first wife, Countess Maria Draskovich of Trakostjan.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/georg-7th-prince-of-waldburg-zeil] Prince Georg died on 2 December 2015 near Leutkirch im Allgäu and was succeeded by his only son, Erich, as head of the princely house.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The **House of Liechtenstein** (German: *Haus Liechtenstein*), from which the principality takes its name, is the family which reigns by hereditary right over the principality of Liechtenstein.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Only dynastic members of the family are eligible to inherit the throne.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The dynasty's membership, rights and responsibilities are defined by a law of the family, which is enforced by the reigning prince and may be altered by vote among the family's dynasts, but which may not be altered by the Government or Parliament of Liechtenstein.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The family originates from Liechtenstein Castle in Lower Austria (near Vienna), which the family possessed from at least 1136 to the 13th century, and from 1807 onwards.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The progenitor Hugo von Liechtenstein (d.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] 1156) built Liechtenstein Castle around 1122-36 on a fief that he received from the Babenberg margraves of Austria.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] He also received Petronell on the Danube and Rohrau Castle, near the then border with the Kingdom of Hungary, at first as a fief, from 1142 as a free property (allod).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] 1265), lord of Liechtenstein and Petronell, was given the lordship of Nikolsburg in southern Moravia as free property from Ottokar II of Bohemia, whom he supported politically, in 1249.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] It remained one of the most important seats until it was sold in 1560.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] In 1394, John I of Liechtenstein, lord of Nikolsburg (d.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] 1397), acquired the Feldsberg estate (then Lower Austria, today Valtice, Czech Republic).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] When he fell out of favor with Albert III, Duke of Austria, for whom he had long conducted government business, he lost his lands south of the Danube, but could keep Nikolsburg because Bohemia and Moravia did not come to the Habsburgs until 1526.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] At the turn of the 16th and 17th centuries, the three brothers Karl, Maximilian and Gundakar initiated a new period in the family history.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The Habsburgs, who ruled the Holy Roman Empire almost continuously until 1806 as Holy Roman Emperors, had always preserved their Catholic faith.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The three brothers supported the ultra-catholic Emperor Ferdinand II in crushing the Bohemian Revolt.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Maximilian, as Field Marshal, won the Battle of White Mountain.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] On diplomatic missions, Gundaker prepared the Catholic League, which fought for the Habsburgs in the Thirty Years' War.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Karl restored order as Viceroy of Bohemia and oversaw the arrests and executions of the 27 Protestant leaders of the uprising.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] For this they were all three made Princes of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] In addition, they were able to cheaply acquire huge lands from expelled and dispossessed Protestant nobles in Bohemia and Moravia, especially since Karl himself, as the Emperor's representative, carried out these confiscations.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] He also received the Duchy of Troppau and the Duchy of Krnov (Jägerndorf) in Silesia from the Emperor.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The respective *Fürst* still holds these two ducal titles to this day.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The Moravian and Bohemian possessions acquired at the time included: Bučovice, Moravská Třebová, Moravský Krumlov, Uherský Ostroh (with Kunovice and Hluk), Šternberk and a palace in Prague (on Malostranské náměstí).
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Most of these estates remained in the possession of the princely house until Czechoslovakia expropriated them in 1945.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] In 1622, Maximilian founded a monastery in Vranov, in whose family crypt almost all Liechtenstein princes were buried, until a new crypt was built in Vaduz in 1960.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The then head of the family, Prince Hans-Adam I, was able to arrange the purchase from the Hohenems family of the minuscule Lordship of Schellenberg in 1699, and the County of Vaduz in 1712.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Schellenberg and Vaduz were indeed a lordship and a county respectively, which were directly subordinate to the emperor as feudal lord.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] On this date, the brand new principality of Liechtenstein became a member state of the Holy Roman Empire whereby the ruling princes became the monarchs of Liechtenstein and they finally received the longed-for hereditary seat in the Reichstag.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] However, the ruling princes did not set foot in their new principality for several decades, a testament to the pure political expediency of the purchases.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Since the small country, far away from Vienna and Bohemia, consisted only of farming villages, the administration was installed in the nearest town, Feldkirch in Austria, where the prince had an office building built for his governor.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Vaduz Castle, the center of the medieval county of that name, remained unused and was rented out as a restaurant for hikers until the late 19th century.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] With the end of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806, the Principality of Liechtenstein became sovereign and was recognized in this status by the Congress of Vienna in 1814/1815.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Johann I became the first sovereign ruler.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] He acquired a number of castles and estates in Austria for his numerous sons, which are still mostly inhabited by their descendants today.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The reigning princes continued to live in their magnificent Vienna residences, Liechtenstein City Palace and Liechtenstein Garden Palace, and on their Moravian and Bohemian estates, with Lednice and Valtice (German names: Eisgrub and Feldsberg) as their main residence.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The border between Austria and Bohemia-Moravia, both member states of the Austro-Hungarian Empire under the Habsburg rule, ran through the park between the two castles.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The local administration of the Principality of Liechtenstein was overseen by a governor, and the government office was located at the prince's seat.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] It was not until the Occupation of Czechoslovakia (1938–1945) by Nazi Germany at the beginning of World War II that the residence was moved from Valtice to Vaduz.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The prince had opposed the annexation of Czech territory, including Valtice and Lednice, into Sudetenland, and as a consequence his properties were confiscated by the Nazis, and the family then relocated to Vaduz in 1939.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Austria had also been annexed by Germany through the *Anschluss* in 1938.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] After the Second World War, not only were the family's Czechoslovak properties expropriated, but in Allied-occupied Austria most of their properties were also located in the Soviet occupation zone and were therefore inaccessible until the end of the occupation in 1955.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Due to the expropriations in Czechoslovakia as a result of the Beneš decrees in 1945, the family lost a large part of their land holdings, with about 1,200 square kilometers (463 square miles), 7.5 times the total area of the Principality itself.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] It was only able to restore its prosperity, including the upkeep of numerous castles in Austria and of the world-famous art collections, in the last quarter of the 20th century by expanding its small Liechtenstein bank into the internationally operating financial company LGT Group.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] According to the Constitution of the Princely House of Liechtenstein of 26 October 1993, all members other than the reigning prince shall bear the titles of Prince or Princess of Liechtenstein and Count or Countess of Rietberg.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] Below are all male and male-line dynastic descendants of Johann I Joseph, Prince of Liechtenstein.
[src:alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil/house-of-liechtenstein] The numbers represent the positions in the line of succession.
